Good observation about Vietnam.  Well, not really.  In fact that is a horrible example and let me tell you why.  The politicians made, pushed, and continued the war in Vietnam.  It was not, NOT, a free country vs. communist country issue.  That is complete bullshit.  It was a war over nationalism, a bogus war that never should have taken place.  There should never have been a North and South Vietnam government and the only reason there was a division between the two at the 17th parallel was to allow two things; the first year was for the French and Communist troops to be separated while the French got out of the country.  The second year was a rebuilding/waiting/political campaigning time for the Vietnamese who, at the end of this two year stretch of time AFTER the Geneva Conference of 1954, were to be allowed to vote on who the new leader of Vietnam would be.  Of course, without a shadow of a doubt, Ho Chi Minh would have won.  So what happened?  Well a Southern REBEL (because that is what it was) government refused to hold a vote and yet Uncle Ho waited six more years before helping the VietCong because he believed the rest of the world would stand behind him based on the Geneva Conference but, of course, that didn’t happen.  So America steps in and funds the Southern government, a government that had a new leader weekly at one point, and told its people that this was a war against Communism and that it must be stopped at the 17th parallel and a bunch of other crap that other governments knew was total B.S.  Wonder why the British didn’t support America in ‘Nam?  Because they thought we were bloody crazy, which we were.  Now did America’s CITIZENS, the people who sit on coaches and produce the money for the military to go buy shinny weapons and shoot things with, ask for the war in Vietnam? No.  But the politicians sure as hell did.  Our government performed a terrorist act against its citizens by entering into a useless war of foreign aggression.  The aggression, of course, was all Americas. <br>
